489
52:30.450 --> 52:36.690
To be precise, the input is
two positive integer A and N for which the GCD is equal to one,

490
52:36.690 --> 52:44.141
and the output is the
smallest positive integer R such that A to the power R is
congruent to one modular N,

491
52:44.141 --> 52:48.960
or equivalently the
smallest positive integer R for which A to the R is equal to one.

492
52:48.960 --> 52:53.370
Assuming we're doing arithmetic in ZN.

493
52:53.370 --> 53:00.960
This is believed to be a
computationally difficult problem, no efficient classical algorithm
is known for solving it.

494
53:00.960 --> 53:08.520
And as we'll discuss the problem is at least as hard as
integer factorization in the sense that if we have an algorithm for solving order finding,

495
53:08.520 --> 53:13.710
we would be able to use that algorithm to solve the integer
factorization problem efficiently.

496
53:13.710 --> 53:21.030
In fact, it goes the other way as well, meaning that if you happen to have an algorithm for factoring, you can use it to solve
the order finding problem.

497
53:21.030 --> 53:26.310
So the two problems are
in some sense equivalent in terms of their
computational difficulty.

498
53:26.310 --> 53:33.570
Now we'll see how we can solve
the order finding problem on a quantum computer
using phase estimation.

499
53:33.570 --> 53:41.970
To make a connection between the problems, let's imagine that we have a system whose classical state set is AN.

500
53:41.970 --> 53:49.530
For any choice of an element A in ZN star, we'll define an operation
MA like we have here.

501
53:49.530 --> 53:56.670
In words what MA does is to multiply by A, and here the multiplication is modular N.

502
53:56.670 --> 54:04.020
And for the remainder of this lesson, you should always think about
expressions inside of cats as being computed modular N,

503
54:04.020 --> 54:10.890
just so we can keep things simple and we don't have to keep on
writing mod N over and over.

504
54:10.890 --> 54:17.220
This is a unitary operation, but that's only true
because A is in ZN star.

505
54:17.220 --> 54:24.150
If the GCD of A and N isn't one, this operation won't be unitary.

506
54:24.150 --> 54:33.450
Here's an example. If N is equal to 15 and A is equal to two, which is in Z 15 star, then
this is the action of M two.

507
54:33.450 --> 54:41.670
And if you examine this
example for a few moments, you'll see that what's happening is that the elements of ZN are just getting permuted by this action.

508
54:41.670 --> 54:51.870
So it's both deterministic and unitary, which is to say that as a matrix, MA is a permutation matrix.

509
54:51.870 --> 54:58.230
And here's the main idea. The eigenvalues of MA are
very closely connected

510
54:58.230 --> 55:04.500
with the order of A. And by using phase estimation to approximate these
eigenvalues closely enough

511
55:04.500 --> 55:11.850
we can determine the order of A. So what exactly are the eigenvectors and the eigenvalues of MA?

512
55:11.850 --> 55:17.700
Well, we're not going to need all of them, we only need some of them.

513
55:17.700 --> 55:22.080
Let's start off with an easy example.

514
55:22.080 --> 55:28.930
Here's an eigenvector of MA, we've named it size zero, and it's given by the
sum of cat one, cat a,

515
55:28.930 --> 55:36.495
cat A squared, and so on up to cat A to the power R minus one, all divided by the square root of R

516
55:36.495 --> 55:40.320
to make it a unit vector. Here R is the order of A.

517
55:40.320 --> 55:44.490
And I'll reserve the
letter R for the order of A for the rest of the lesson.

518
55:44.490 --> 55:51.876
So whenever you see R, that's the order of A for
whatever A we're talking about.

519
55:51.876 --> 55:55.710
The eigenvalue associated
with this eigenvector is one.

520
55:55.710 --> 56:01.740
And we can verify that by
applying MA to this vector to see what we get.

521
56:01.740 --> 56:10.020
MA multiplies by A, so
we just need to increase each of the exponents by
one and this is what we get.

522
56:10.020 --> 56:14.700
But the order of A is R, so A to the power R equals one.

523
56:14.700 --> 56:18.930
And we can make that substitution.

524
56:18.930 --> 56:27.240
But that's the same vector
that we started with. All we've done is to
shuffle the cuts around but we're taking the sum so
this doesn't change anything.

525
56:27.240 --> 56:31.380
So MA times psi zero is equal to psi zero.

526
56:31.380 --> 56:35.400
So it's an eigenvector of
MA with eigenvalue one.

527
56:35.400 --> 56:43.080
That's a very simple
example of an eigenvector and to identify more of them, let's recall the same notation that we had earlier in the lesson.

528
56:43.080 --> 56:49.260
Omega R is the complex
number on the unit circle we get by taking E to the
power of two times pi times I

529
56:49.260 --> 56:57.720
divided by R. Last time we had an N rather than an R, but it still works the same
way for R in place of N.

530
56:57.720 --> 57:04.890
We need this number because
it's going to be appearing in the other eigenvectors
of MA that we'll identify.

531
57:04.890 --> 57:12.870
And now that we've recalled that notation, we can observe that this
vector named psi one is also an eigenvector of MA.

532
57:12.870 --> 57:19.500
It's similar to psi zero, we have exactly the same cats and we're summing them up and
dividing by the square of R.

533
57:19.500 --> 57:23.910
But this time we have various phases multiplying each of the cats.

534
57:23.910 --> 57:33.930
Omega R to the negative one for A, omega R to the negative two for A squared, and so on up to omega R to
the power negative R minus one

535
57:33.930 --> 57:45.570
for A to the power R minus one. So the power of omega R
is always negative one times whatever power of A
appears inside of the cat.

536
57:45.570 --> 57:52.650
I won't go through it in detail, but it is shown on the screen in case you'd like to re-watch the video and pause as needed.

537
57:52.650 --> 57:59.160
But if we do the multiplication and we simplify again using the fact that A to the power R is equal to one

538
57:59.160 --> 58:07.680
as well as the very important fact that omega to the power R is equal to one, what we'll find is that we
again have an eigenvector of MA.

